    [[maybe_unused]] bool NeedToExit;
    (void)AttemptCheckBitwidth(Checker, NeedToExit);
```
Ah! `AttemptCheckBitwidth` is called with the cost `Checker`, which always returns `false`. So it iterates through all bitwidths and finds the one with the best cost.
Then it calls `TryProcessInstruction`:
```cpp
    return TryProcessInstruction(I, *ITE, BitWidth, Operands, CallChecker);
```
Inside `TryProcessInstruction`:
```cpp
          if (Checker && !AttemptCheckBitwidth(Checker, NeedToExit))
            return false;
```
Wait, `TryProcessInstruction` calls `AttemptCheckBitwidth` AGAIN, this time with `CallChecker`!
But for `Intrinsic::abs`, `CallChecker` is empty!
```cpp
    if (ID != Intrinsic::abs) {
      Operands.push_back(I->getOperand(1));
      End = 2;
      CallChecker = CompChecker;
    }
```
If `CallChecker` is empty, `TryProcessInstruction` does:
```cpp
          if (Checker && !AttemptCheckBitwidth(Checker, NeedToExit))
            return false;
```
Since `Checker` (which is `CallChecker`) is empty, it skips this check!
This means for `Intrinsic::abs`, it NEVER checks if the operands can actually be safely truncated! It just assumes they can be truncated to `BitWidth` (which was determined by the users of the `abs` instruction, e.g., a `trunc` instruction).
Is it always safe to truncate the operand of `abs`?
Suppose we have `trunc (abs i32 %x) to i8`.
Can we replace this with `abs i8 (trunc i32 %x to i8)`?
Let's check:
If `%x = 129` (0x00000081).
`abs(%x)` = 129.
`trunc(129) to i8` = -127 (0x81).
If we truncate first:
`trunc(%x) to i8` = -127 (0x81).
`abs(-127)` = 127 (0x7F).
These are NOT equal! `-127 != 127`.
So `trunc (abs %x)` is NOT equivalent to `abs (trunc %x)` in general!
It is only equivalent if the sign bit of the truncated type matches the sign bit of the original type, or something like that. Specifically, we need `SignBits <= ComputeNumSignBits(%x)`.
But the patch completely omits `CallChecker` for `Intrinsic::abs`!
Let's verify this.
If `ID == Intrinsic::abs`, `CallChecker` is not assigned.
So `TryProcessInstruction` will just process the operand `%x` and try to demote it to `BitWidth` without any value checks!
This is a massive bug. `abs` cannot be arbitrarily truncated.
